defaultPART A – Introduction to the Current Funding of Support in Homelessness Provision default&#xa0;default1) Homelessness hostels and supported housing projects are curr
defaultently funded by two main sources. The first is Housing Benefit (HB) which pays for both core rents and housing management costs where clients are not working or are on a low income. Because of the extra running costs of this type of provision, the level of
default HB is not usually capped by Local Housing Allowance (LHA) Rates. However, the amount of HB councils will pay and the subsidy they can receive back from central government will vary depending on the status of the provider of the accommodation. 
default2) The Gove
defaultrnment’s current plan is to phase-out HB by the end of 2017. At which point the costs currently met by HB will have had to transfer to Universal Credit (UC) unless an alternative funding approach has been developed by then. Ministers have stated publicly t
defaulthat their intention is to move to a “localised solution” by then
default. Our thoughts on this overall approach are outlined in 
defaultP
defaultar
defaultt C
default of this submission
default.
default3) Prior to
default around
default 2003, Housing Benefit was also used to fund support in homelessness projects. However, at that point the Supporting People (SP) programme was introduced to pay for “housing-related support” and HB was limited to the areas identified in paragraph 1. SP was
default paid through a “ring-fenced grant” to councils based on levels of local need
default.
default 
default4) The 
defaultactivities that were included
default under the heading “housing related support” and therefore eligible for funding under SP was varied
default:
default - life and social skills
default;
default managing debt
defaults
default;
default budgeting
default;
default applying for benefits
default;
default resettlement support
default;
default understanding bills
default;
default developin
defaultg
default support networks
default;
default activities promoting training, education and employment within the community
default;
default and helping individuals deal with other agencies 
defaultincluding
default health and
default advice services. 
default5) In 2009 the “ring-fence” was removed from the SP budget. 
defaultWith
default local authorities 
defaultfacing
default year-on-year cuts in Formula Grant
default,
default many have 
defaultmade disproportionate cuts to their SP budgets with homelessness services facing reduction
defaults
default to funding as
default high as 81%
default and even 100%
default. 
defaultThis has already led to the loss of vital support in many areas.
