defaultPart C- The Future of Funding Of Support in Homelessness Provisiondefault3
default4
default) 
defaultHomelessness and 
defaulthousing-related support services deliver cost savings to public service budgets and better outcomes for vulnerable people. The more services can support people to move away from homelessness and towards independent living, the more they can reduce their ex
defaultpensive use of public services, and so be more cost efficient
default.
default Without the support from homelessness services, more people would end up sleeping rough and 
defaultusing costly services
default.
default It is critical that a longer term strategy is developed which recognises the
default investment needed to achieve these longer term savings.
default&#xa0;
default3
default5
default) 
defaultAs outlined 
defaultin 
defaultPart A, the Government’s short-term intention is to try and keep housing costs for homelessness projects outside of UC whilst a “localised solution” is developed. We envisage this
default meaning that funding of housing management costs in homelessness services will no longer be administered through DWP, instead being devolved to councils or 
defaultan
defaultother body.  
default3
default6
default) This would align Housing Management costs with the funding of support which is already the responsibility of council. It could also draw a line under a twenty-year debate as to 
defaulthow 
defaultsupport
defaulted 
defaulthousing should be primarily funded. However, despite this obvio
defaultus appeal of this approach to Government, 
defaultwe
default ha
defaultve
default a number of concerns and lessons from history 
defaultwe
default would like to draw the Committee’s attention to.
default3
default7
default) Our most obvious fear is that any localised funding will suffer the same fate as Supporting People. In t
defaulthe current local government economic environment, any unring-fenced budget is at risk of being diverted to other priorities. Whilst the rationale of localism is that councils know best about need in their area, we worry that in some areas “politically unpo
defaultpular” groups will not be helped as we have already witnessed in recent local funding decisions. 
default38
default)
default 
defaultIt
default is essential that any
default 
defaultlocalised solution either needs to come with a ring
default-
defaultfence or some form of statutory protection for homeless people.
default T
defaulthe introduct
defaultion of Local Welfare Assistance has shown how homeless people with their lack of
default sustained, provable
default connection to any single area particularly suffer under purely localised approaches.
default39
default) We also hope that any changes to the funding of homelessness services does not allow the progress made in quality of provision over the last 25 years to be undermined. The Department for Communities and Local Government (DCLG) and its predecessors have i
defaultnvested hundreds of millions of pounds in turning homelessness buildings from 
defaultdehumanising 
defaultinstitutions 
defaultin
defaultto places of change. 
default4
default0
default) Furthermore, a partnership of central and local government with homelessness agencies has led to quantum leaps in creating s
defaultervices which emphasise helping people out of homelessness by progressing them back into the community and supporting them develop work, training and employment skills. The failure of the Work Programme has shown how challenging it can be to engage with vu
defaultlnerable clients
default.
default 
default Homelessness services can continue do it, but not without investment.
default4
default1
default) Homeless Link believes the development of future funding needs to emphasise client choice which helps foster a spirit of personal responsibility. We have seen tha
defaultt “Personalisation” approaches have successfully engaged with 
defaultsome of the
default most entrenched rough sleepers
